<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-053-914  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 053 914.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 13 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T, MCI back in court again. (MCI Communications Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (cases)MCI Communications Corp. (cases)Pioneer Teletechnologies Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsCourt CasesDeceptive Advertising.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ATandamp;T, MCI BACK IN COURT AGAIN NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990 JAN 10 (NB) --ATandamp;T and MCI are back in court again.andP;  This time, the bigger company isaccusing its smaller rival of unfair and deceptive telemarketing practicesand switching of long-distance customers without their consent.andM;The ATandamp;T lawsuit, filed in U.S.andP;  District Court for the District of NewJersey, charges MCI and Pioneer Teletechnologies with usingmisrepresentations of facts to induce ATandamp;T customers to switch theirlong-distance service.andP;  ATandamp;T said, for example, that MCI salesrepresentatives have told ATandamp;T customers that ATandamp;T is no longer handlinglong-distance calls, or in some cases saying that ATandamp;T is going out ofbusiness.andP;  The lawsuit also charges that MCI and Pioneer representatives haveswitched ATandamp;T customers to MCI without their knowledge or consent.andM;Pioneer is a telemarketing agent headquartered in Sergeant Bluff, Iowa, andis 25% owned by MCI.andM;The suit asks that MCI stop making false, misleading or deceptive claimsabout ATandamp;T, and stop switching ATandamp;T long-distance customers to MCI withoutauthorization.andP;  In addition, ATandamp;T has asked to be awarded damages it hassuffered as a consequence of the MCI and Pioneer wrongful conduct.andM;ATandamp;T also asked for a rule change from the Federal Communications Commission,stating that long-distance companies must obtain written customer permissionbefore notifying local telephone companies of a customer's selection of along-distance carrier.andM;ATandamp;T said its preliminary studies show that between February and November1989 that 10-15% of monthly conversions of ATandamp;T residential customers toother long-distance companies involved customers who either had never beencontacted by the other company or had declined to switch.andP;  Many customerswere initially unaware that they had been switched to another carrier.andM;MCI denied the charges, and is considering a countersuit.andP;  &quot;This is justanother example of ATandamp;T preaching competition on the one hand and whiningwhen it takes place,&quot; an MCI spokesman told Newsbytes.andP;  &quot;We've been winningcustomers at a rate of 100,000 per week.andP;  We view this action as an exampleof frustration and their attempts to impede competition in the marketplace.&quot;andO;On the proposed rule change, the MCI spokesman called it ironic and saidthey'd oppose the rule change.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900112/Press Contact: Bruce Reid, ATandamp;T, 201- 221-8413;John Houser, MCI Corporate Communications, 800-289- 0073)</TEXT></DOC>